comments.body: Adults might feed on slugs, per a 1934 article by Leech et al.

Per BugGuide, this species is found there: https://bugguide.net/node/view/32505/data. As an aside, these beetles apparently denude their dead things after burying them, then apply some sort of saliva that might be preservative in function. Both parents then patrol body to remove any dipteran larvae that might find the corpse. Really cool, though that might be tmi.
It may have hitched a ride to the Pacific NW in someone’s RV or firewood since I found it in a campsite.

I am tentatively agreeing with the ID.  I've spent an hour trying to confirm, but will wait for the NW Entomology Facebook group to weigh in.  I posted it there for feedback.  Someone suggest the Valentine Beetle, which led me off on a merry chase before I realized they might be joking!  If N. defodiens, which is likely, the hearts were just a very lucky individual color variation.
